{"title_page": "National Technical University of Athens", "text_new": "{{Hatnote|NTUA redirects here. For the Taiwanese university, see [[National Taiwan University of Arts]].}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name         = National (Metsovian) Technical University of Athens\n| native_name  = \u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039c\u03b5\u03c4\u03c3\u03cc\u03b2\u03b9\u03bf \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\n| latin_name   = \n| motto        = \n| image        = Pyrforos2.png\n| caption      = Seal of NTUA\n| established  = December 31, 1836 {{small|[[Adoption of the Gregorian calendar#Adoption in Eastern Europe|(OS)]]}}<br />  January 21, 1837 {{small|(NS)}}<ref name=\"Ntua History Greek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/history2.html|script-title=el:\u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1|publisher=NTUA.gr|language=Greek|accessdate=2009-03-30|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502181741/http://www.ntua.gr/history2.html|archivedate=2012-05-02}}</ref>\n| type         = [[Public university|Public]]<br />[[Higher education|Higher Education Institution]]<br />[[List of universities in Greece|Greece University System]]\n| endowment    = \n| staff        = 1350<ref name=\"NTUA Schools\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/schools_en.html|title=NTUA Schools|publisher=NTUA.gr|accessdate=2009-01-28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090129180735/http://www.ntua.gr/schools_en.html|archivedate=2009-01-29}}</ref>\n| faculty      = \n| president    = \n| provost      = \n| principal    = \n| rector       = Andreas Boudouvis<ref>https://www.ntua.gr/en/ntua/members-and-administrator</ref>\n| dean         = \n| head_label   = \n| head         = \n| students     = \n| undergrad    = 8500<ref name=\"NTUA Schools\"/>\n| postgrad     = 1500<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/postgraduate_en.html|title=Postgraduate Studies|publisher=NTUA.gr|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915094042/http://www.ntua.gr/postgraduate_en.html|archivedate=2014-09-15}}</ref>\n| doctoral     = \n| city         = [[Athens]]\n| state        = \n| country      = [[Greece]]\n| campus       = [[Patission Avenue|Patision]] Complex <br/> <small>''(central [[Athens]])''</small>, <br/> [[Zografou]] campus <br/> <small>''([[Central Athens]] district)''</small><ref name=\"General Information\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/contact_en.html|title=General Information|publisher=NTUA.gr|accessdate=2009-01-28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120701103003/http://www.ntua.gr/contact_en.html|archivedate=2012-07-01}}</ref>\n| free_label   = Also known as\n| free         = Athens Polytechnic <br />National Metsovian Polytechnic\n| colors       = [[White]] and [[Gold (color)|Gold]] {{Color box|#ffffff|border=darkgray}}{{Color box|#f1b93e|border=darkgray}}\n| colours      = \n| mascot       = [[Prometheus]]\n| nickname     = \n| affiliations = [[Top Industrial Managers for Europe|TIME]], [[CESAER Association|CESAER]]\n| website      = {{url|www.ntua.gr}}\n| athletics    = 40 sports\n| logo         = \n}}\n\nThe '''National''' ('''Metsovian''') '''Technical University of Athens''' ('''NTUA'''; {{lang-el|\u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039c\u03b5\u03c4\u03c3\u03cc\u03b2\u03b9\u03bf \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03bf}}, ''National Metsovian Polytechnic''), sometimes known as '''Athens Polytechnic''', is among the oldest higher education institutions of [[Greece]] and the most prestigious among engineering schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2016|date=January 1, 2016|accessdate=2016-11-29|title=QS World University Rankings 2016-2017}}</ref> It is named ''Metsovio(n)'' in honor of its benefactors Nikolaos Stournaris, Eleni Tositsa, Michail Tositsas and Georgios Averoff, whose origin is from the town of [[Metsovo]] in [[Epirus (region)|Epirus]].<ref name=\"NTUA History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/history_en.html|title=History|publisher=NTUA.gr|accessdate=2009-03-30|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090401190941/http://www.ntua.gr/history_en.html|archivedate=2009-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIt was founded in 1837 as a part-time vocational school named '''Royal School of Arts''' which, as its role in the technical development of the fledgling state grew, developed into Greece's sole institution providing engineering degrees up until the 1950s, when polytechnics were established outiside [[Athens]]. Its traditional [[campus]], located in the center of Athens on [[Patision Avenue]], features a suite of magnificent neo-[[classical architecture|classical]] buildings by architect Lysandros Kaftantzoglou (1811\u20131885). A new campus, the [[Zografou]] Campus, was built in the 1980s.<ref name=\"NTUA History\" />\n\nNTUA is divided into nine academic schools, eight being for the [[engineering]] disciplines, including [[architecture]], and one for applied [[sciences]] (mathematics and physics). Undergraduate studies have a duration of five years. Admission to NTUA is highly selective and can only be accomplished through achieving exceptional grades in the annual [[Panhellenic Examinations|Panhellenic Exams]]. It is a widely spread perception that the vast majority of each year's Panhellenic Exams top students interested in the sciences and technology opts to attend NTUA. The university comprises about 700 of academic staff, 140 scientific assistants and 260 administrative and technical staff. It also has about 8,500 undergraduates and about 1,500 postgraduate students.<ref name=\"NTUA Schools\" /> Eight of the NTUA's Schools are housed at the Zografou Campus, while the School of Architecture is based at the Patision Complex.\n\n==History==\nNTUA was established by [[Kingdom of Greece (Wittelsbach)|royal]] decree on December 31, 1836 [[Adoption of the Gregorian calendar#Adoption in Eastern Europe|(OS)]], January 21, 1837 (NS), under the name  \"Royal School of Arts\" (\u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03a3\u03c7\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bf \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03a4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd).<ref name=\"Ntua History Greek\" /> It began functioning as a part-time vocational school (only Sundays and holidays) to train craftsmen, builders and master craftsmen to cover the needs of the [[History of modern Greece|new Greek state]]. In 1840, due to its increasing popularity and the changing socio-economic conditions in the new state, NTUA was upgraded to a daily technical school which worked along with the Sunday school. The courses were expanded and the institution was housed in its own building in [[Pireos Street]].<ref name=\"Ntua History Greek\" />\n\n===The restructuring===\nIn 1843 a major restructuring was made. Three departments were created:\n\n* ''Part-Time Vocational School''\n* ''Daily School''\n* A new ''Higher School of Fine Arts''\n\nThe new department's object was fine arts and engineering. The new department, which was later renamed ''School of Industrial and Fine Arts'', rapidly evolved towards a major higher education institution. Tradition has it that ''arts'' referred to both technical professions and fine arts. Even today, the school maintains a school of architecture that is closely related to the School of Fine Arts, which later evolved to become a separate school.\n\nThe name ''Polytechnnic'' came in 1862, with the introduction of several new technical courses. This restructuring continued steadily until 1873. At the time, the school became overwhelmed by the plethora of students wanting to learn high technical skills, and this led to its moving to a new campus.\n\n===The relocation===\n[[File:NTUA - Patision Complex.jpg|right|thumb|340px|The historical Patision Street campus in a postcard of 1900.]]\n[[File:NTUA Averof Building Main Facade.jpg|thumb|240px|The main facade of the Averof building today.]]\n\nIn 1873 it moved to its new campus in [[Patision Street]] and was known as ''Metsovion Polytechnion'' (Metsovian Polytechnic) after the birthplace of its benefactors who financed the construction of this campus. At the time, the campus in Patision Street was even partially incomplete, but the high demand by students made it urgent to rellocate.\n\nIn 1887, the institution was partitioned into three schools of technical orientation, the schools of Structural Engineering, Architecture and Mechanical Engineering, all four-year degrees at the time. This is when the institute was recognized as a technical education facility by the state, which was a crucial step for its development, as it became accompanied to the country's needs as it developed.\n\nIn 1914, new schools were created and was officially named ''Ethnicon Metsovion Polytechnion'' (National Metsovian Polytechnic) went under the supervision of the Ministry of Public Works. This is when new technical schools started to be formed, a procedure was completed three years later, in 1917 when the NTUA changed form: By special law, the old ''School of Industrial Arts'' was now separated into the Higher Schools of ''Civil Engineering'', ''Mechanical&nbsp;&amp; Electrical Engineering'', ''Chemical Engineering'', ''Surveying Engineering'' and ''Architecture''. Later, the schools of ''Naval Engineering'', and ''Mining and Metallurgical Engineering'' were formed, and the school of ''Mechanical&nbsp;&amp; Electrical Engineering'' was split up into two separate schools, ''Mechanical Engineering'' and ''Electrical and Computer Engineering'', which is almost the form of schools maintained until now.\n\nIn 1923, the NTUA alumni formed the core of the [[Technical Chamber of Greece]], the professional organization that serves as the official technical adviser of the [[Greek state]] and is responsible for awarding professional licenses to all practicing engineers in Greece.<ref name=\"NTUA History\" />\n\nIn 1930, the [[Athens School of Fine Arts]] was established, acquiring its independence from the NTUA, as a school exclusively focused in the teaching the fine arts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asfa.gr/greek/ASKT/info/info01.htm|date=September 20, 2010|accessdate=2010-09-20|title=\u0391\u03bd\u03ce\u03c4\u03b1\u03c4\u03b7 \u03a3\u03c7\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae \u039a\u03b1\u03bb\u03ce\u03bd \u03a4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd&nbsp;\u2013 \u038a\u03b4\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03b7 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03a3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03cc\u03c2}}</ref> This allowed the two schools to develop separately as a technical and an arts school respectively.\n\nIn 1941 to 1944, the National Technical University of Athens played an important role in the country's political life with the Greek students participating in the [[Greek Resistance|National Resistance]] under the German occupation. During the [[Axis occupation of Greece during World War II|Axis occupation of Greece]], NTUA, in addition to its function as an academic institution, became one of the most active [[Greek Resistance#Resistance in the cities|resistance]] centers in Athens.\n\n===The uprising===\n{{main|Athens Polytechnic uprising}}\nThe most important event of NTUA's history is the [[Athens Polytechnic uprising]] on November 17, 1973, which was the first step to overthrow [[Greek military junta of 1967-1974|Greece's military dictatorship]].\nOn 14, 15 and 16 of November 1973, the students were barricaded inside the institute, and started broadcasting a pirate radio transmission, calling the people of Athens to rebel. In the evening of November 17 however, an AMX-30 class military tank broke the main gate and charged inside, after receiving orders from the dictators. About 23 people were killed in the following events and the uprising ended. The junta however, was irreparably damaged by the popular outcry. The junta fell in 1974, after the Turkish invasion in Cyprus and since then, November 17 is celebrated as a day of freedom and democracy. All schools and universities of the country remain closed on that day.<ref name=\"NTUA History\" />\n\n==Emblem==\nThe emblem of the National Technical University of Athens is [[Prometheus]].\n\n==Academic profile==\n\n===Schools===\nThe National Technical University of Athens is divided into nine academic schools ({{lang-el|\u03c3\u03c7\u03bf\u03bb\u03ad\u03c2}}), which are furthermore divided into 33 departments (Greek: \u03c4\u03bf\u03bc\u03b5\u03af\u03c2):<ref name=\"NTUA Schools\"/>\n\n*School of [[Applied Mathematics]] and [[Physics]]\n*School of [[Electrical and Computer Engineering]]\n*School of [[Civil Engineering]]\n*School of [[Mechanical Engineering]]\n*School of [[Architecture]]\n*School of [[Chemical Engineering]]\n*School of Rural and [[Surveying Engineering]]\n*School of Mining and [[Metallurgical Engineering]]\n*School of [[Naval Architecture]] and [[Marine Engineering]]\n{{hidden begin|border=solid 1px #aaa|title={{center|Departments by School}}}} \n* [http://semfe.ntua.gr '''School of [[Applied Mathematics]] and [[Physics]]''']\n** [http://www.math.ntua.gr/en_index.html Department of [[Mathematics]]]\n** [http://www.physics.ntua.gr Department of [[Physics]]]\n**[https://web.archive.org/web/20070526223207/http://www.mechan.ntua.gr/en/index.html Department of Mechanics]\n** [http://www.aked.ntua.gr Department of Humanities, Social Sciences and Law]\n* [http://www.ece.ntua.gr '''School of Electrical and Computer Engineering''']\n** [http://www.ece.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_divisions&task=division&id=3&Itemid=60&lang=en Department of Signals, Controls and Robotics]\n** [http://www.ece.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_divisions&task=division&id=4&Itemid=60&lang=en Department of Computer Science]\n** [http://www.ece.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_divisions&task=division&id=6&Itemid=60&lang=en Department of \u0395lectric Power]\n** [http://www.ece.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_divisions&task=division&id=1&Itemid=60&lang=en Department of Electromagnetics, Electrooptics and Electronic Materials]\n** [http://www.ece.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_divisions&task=division&id=7&Itemid=60&lang=en Department of Industrial Electric Devices and Decision Systems]\n** [http://www.ece.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_divisions&task=division&id=5&Itemid=60&lang=en Department of Communications, Electronics and Information Systems]\n** [http://www.ece.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_divisions&task=division&id=2&Itemid=60&lang=en Department of Information Transmission Systems and Material Technology]\n* [http://www.civil.ntua.gr '''School of Civil Engineering''']\n** [https://archive.today/20070619083625/http://www.civil.ntua.gr/new/htdocs/main.php?show=isaar&lang=en Department of Structural Engineering]\n** [http://www.hydro.ntua.gr Department of Water Resources, Hydraulic and Maritime Engineering]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20060418003622/http://www.civil.ntua.gr/new/htdocs/main.php?show=traffic&lang=en Department of Transportation Planning and Engineering]\n** [http://www.civil.ntua.gr/geotech/index.php?lang=en Department of Geotechnical Engineering]\n** [http://cem.civil.ntua.gr/ Department of Engineering Construction and Management]\n[[File:NTUA mechanical engineers school.jpg|right|thumb|240px|View of the School of Mechanical Engineering.]]\n* [http://www.mech.ntua.gr/en'''School of Mechanical Engineering''']\n** [http://fluid.ntua.gr Department of Fluid Mechanics Engineering]\n** Department of Thermal Engineering\n** [http://nuclear.ntua.gr Department of Nuclear Engineering]\n** [http://csl.mech.ntua.gr Department of Mechanical Constructions and Automatic Control]\n** [http://www.mech.ntua.gr/en/sections/TTK Department of Manufacturing Technology]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20130728153211/http://www.mech.ntua.gr/en/sections/TBD_EE Department of Industrial Management and Operational Research]\n* [http://www.arch.ntua.gr '''School of Architecture''']\n** Department of Architectural Design\n** Department of Urban and Regional Planning\n** Department of Interior Design and Landscaping\n** Department of Building Technology-Structural Design and Mechanical Equipment\n* [http://www.chemeng.ntua.gr '''School of Chemical Engineering''']\n** Department of Chemical Sciences\n** [http://www.chemeng.ntua.gr/main.php?tomeas2 Department of Process and Systems Analysis, Design and Development]\n** Department of Materials Science and Engineering\n** Department of Synthesis and Development of Industrial Processes\n* [http://www.survey.ntua.gr/en '''School of Rural and Surveying Engineering''']\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20141027084228/http://www.survey.ntua.gr/en/departments/topo.html Department of Topography]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20141027084143/http://www.survey.ntua.gr/en/departments/geo.html Department of Geography and Regional Planning]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20141027084128/http://www.survey.ntua.gr/en/departments/infrastructure.html Department of Infrastructure and Rural Development]\n* [http://www.metal.ntua.gr '''School of Mining and Metallurgical Engineering''']\n** Department of Geological Sciences\n** Department of Mining Engineering\n** Department of Metallurgy and Materials Technology\n* [http://www.naval.ntua.gr '''School of Naval Architecture and Marine Engineering''']\n** Department of Ship Design & Maritime Transport\n** Department of Ship Hydrodynamics\n** Department of Marine Engineering\n** Department of Marine Structures\n{{hidden end}}\n\n===Studies===\n\n====Undergraduate studies====\nThe academic calendar of NTUA comprises 10 independent, integral academic semesters. Each semester lasts 18 weeks: 13 weeks of classes, a two-week break (Christmas and Easter holidays for the fall and spring semester respectively), and three weeks of semester exams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/old/en_academics/undergr.htm|title=NTUA Undergraduate Studies|accessdate=2013-08-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807201303/http://www.ntua.gr/old/en_academics/undergr.htm|archivedate=2013-08-07}}</ref> The 10th semester is devoted to the preparation of the diploma thesis. The diploma thesis has to be related to one of the courses of the faculty. The student has at his or her disposal at least a full academic semester to prepare the thesis. Upon completion of the thesis, the student must take part in an oral examination that can take place either in June, October or February, after the final examinations, provided that the student has passed all courses prescribed by the curriculum.\n\nAn important part of the studies in NTUA are the summer \"training\" projects which take place in Industrial and Production Units, in the period between the end of the spring semester and the beginning of the fall semester. They constitute an elective course for the Faculties of Civil Engineering, Survey Engineering (Surveying and Geodesy Camp) and Mining and Metallurgy Engineering (Mining Camp) and are partially subsidized by the European Union.\n\n====Postgraduate studies====\nThere are currently 20<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntua.gr/el/school/postgraduate-studies|script-title=el:\u039c\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03c0\u03c4\u03c5\u03c7\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03b4\u03ad\u03c2|last=George|website=www.ntua.gr|language=el-gr|access-date=2018-07-01}}</ref> departmental or inter-departmental postgraduate courses, coordinated by NTUA Departments, leading to the respective Post Graduate Specialization Diploma, with a minimum duration of 17 months, including one in Business Administration<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://athensmba.ntua.gr/|title=Athens MBA|website=http://athensmba.ntua.gr/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725161742/http://athensmba.ntua.gr/|archive-date=2010-07-25|url-status=dead}}</ref> (in collaboration with the Athens University of Economics and Business). Moreover, NTUA participates in nine post-graduate programs coordinated by other Greek Universities. After the acquisition of the Post Graduate Specialization Diploma, the student can proceed towards submitting a doctoral thesis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/postgraduate_en.html|title=NTUA Postgraduate Studies|accessdate=2013-08-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807141924/http://www.ntua.gr/postgraduate_en.html|archivedate=2013-08-07}}</ref>\n\n===Academic staff===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+NTUA Academic staff per school\n|+\n|-  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"350px\" | School\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\" | [[Lecturers]]\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\" | '''Associate professors'''\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\" | '''Assistant professors'''\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\" | '''[[Professors]]'''\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\" | '''[[Emeritus]]'''\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\" | '''Total'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| School of [[Applied Mathematics]] and [[Physics]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.semfe.ntua.gr/|title=NTUA, School of Applied Mathematics and Physics|accessdate=2013-08-12}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 5 || 35 || 27 || 40 || 13 || 120\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| School of [[Electrical and Computer Engineering]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ece.ntua.gr/en/staff/faculty|title=NTUA, School of Electrical and Computer Engineering, Faculty|accessdate=2017-09-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161215060953/http://www.ece.ntua.gr/en/staff/faculty|archivedate=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 1 || 11 || 12 || 52 || 20 || 96\n|-\n|  style=\"width:350px; text-align:left;\"| School of [[Civil Engineering]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.civil.ntua.gr/staff/|title=NTUA, School of Civil Engineering, Staff|accessdate=2013-08-12}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; text-align:left;\"| 12 || 16 || 17 || 23 || 13 || 81\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| School of [[Mechanical Engineering]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mech.ntua.gr/gr/staff|title=NTUA, School of Mechanical Engineering, Staff|accessdate=2013-08-12|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131027102306/http://www.mech.ntua.gr/gr/staff|archivedate=2013-10-27}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 5 || 12 || 8 || 20 || 10 || 55\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| School of [[Architecture]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arch.ntua.gr/staff/67/125|title=NTUA, School of Architecture, Staff|accessdate=2013-08-12}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 18 || 20 || 9 || 34 || 38 || 119\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| School of [[Chemical Engineering]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chemeng.ntua.gr/the_staff|title=NTUA, School of Chemical Engineering, Staff|accessdate=2013-08-12}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 6 || 13 || 10 || 48 || - || 77\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| School of Rural and [[Surveying Engineering]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.survey.ntua.gr/el/deplist|title=NTUA, School of Rural and Surveying Engineering, list of Academic staff|accessdate=2013-08-12|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908050312/http://www.survey.ntua.gr/el/deplist|archivedate=2013-09-08}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 7 || 14 || 5 ||15 || 8 || 49\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| School of Mining and [[Metallurgical Engineering]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metal.ntua.gr/index.pl/staff_gr_dep|title=NTUA, School of CMining and Metallurgical Engineering, Staff|accessdate=2013-08-12}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 4 || 10 || 9 ||14 || 14 || 51\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| School of [[Naval Architecture]] and [[Marine Engineering]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naval.ntua.gr/faculty|title=NTUA, School Naval Architecture and Marine Engineering, Staff|accessdate=2013-08-12}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 0 || 4 || 5 || 15 || 5 || 29\n|}\n\n==Academic evaluation==\nAn external evaluation of all academic departments in [[List of universities in Greece|Greek universities]] will be conducted by the [[Hellenic Quality Assurance and Accreditation Agency]] (HQAA) in the following years.<ref>[http://www.adip.gr/index.php?lang=en Hellenic Quality Assurance and Accreditation Agency]</ref>\n\n* School of Naval Architecture and Marine Engineering (2012) <ref>[http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_NavalArchMarineEng_%202012.pdf HQAA Final Report - School of Naval Architecture and Marine Engineering, NTUA, 2012]</ref>\n* School of Mechanical Engineering (2012) <ref>[http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_MechEng_2012.pdf HQAA Final Report - School of Mechanical Engineering, NTUA, 2012]</ref>\n* School of Civil Engineering (2013) <ref>[http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_CivilEng_2013.pdf HQAA Final Report - School of Civil Engineering, NTUA, 2013]</ref>\n* School of Electrical and Computer Engineering (2013) <ref>[http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_ElecCompEng_2013.pdf HQAA Final Report - School of Electrical and Computer Engineering, NTUA, 2013]</ref>\n* School of Mining and Metallurgical Engineering (2013) <ref>[http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_MiningMetalEng_2013.pdf HQAA Final Report - School of Mining and Metallurgical Engineering, NTUA, 2013]</ref>\n* School of Chemical Engineering (2013) <ref>[http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_ChemEng_2013.pdf HQAA Final Report - School of Chemical Engineering, NTUA, 2013]</ref>\n* School of Applied Mathematical & Physical Science (2013) <ref>[http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_ApplMathPhysical_2013.pdf HQAA Final Report - School of Applied Mathematical & Physical Science, NTUA, 2013]</ref>\n* School of Rural and Surveying Engineering (2014) <ref>[http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_RuralSurveyingEng_2013.pdf HQAA Final Report - School of Rural and Surveying Engineering, NTUA, 2014]</ref>\n* School of Architecture (2014) <ref>[http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_Architecture_2014.pdf HQAA Final Report - School of Architecture, NTUA, 2014]</ref>\n\n==Research and innovation==\nNTUA boasts high research activity, as research and education are both its goals. Research is managed by administrative and education personnel, but can be conducted by graduate and sometimes undergraduate students as well. Research is administrated by five different offices:\n# The Special Accounting for Research Office (\u0395\u039b\u039a\u0395)\n# The Liaison Office <ref>[http://dasta.ntua.gr/dasta/index.php/en/ DASTA NTUA - Employment and Career Structure, retrieved 2014] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203135604/http://dasta.ntua.gr/dasta/index.php/en/ |date=2014-02-03 }}</ref>\n# The Innovation and Entrepreneurship Unit <ref>[http://mke.ntua.gr/ IEU NTUA - Innovation and Entrepreneurship Unit NTUA, retrieved 2014]</ref>\n# The Internship Programme <ref>[http://dasta.ntua.gr/coop-en/ Internship Programme NTUA, retrieved 2014] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203135602/http://dasta.ntua.gr/coop-en/ |date=2014-02-03 }}</ref>\n# The Office of Researchers\n# The Interdisciplinary Research Center\n# The Interdisciplinary Unit for Reusable Energy\n\nResearch is funded by the NTUA endowment, or often directly through public or private funds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/old/gr_academics/research.htm|accessdate=2010-09-22|title=NTUA Research|publisher=NTUA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100820131341/http://www.ntua.gr/old/gr_academics/research.htm|archivedate=2010-08-20}}</ref>\n\n===Ranking===\nThe National Technical university of Athens is ranked 338th in the world, 116th in the European Union and 3rd in Greece by the Webometrics Ranking of World Universities website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webometrics.info/en/search/Rankings/National%20Technical%20University%20of%20Athens%20type%3Amundial|title=Ranking of World Universities, CSIS|accessdate=2013-10-17}}</ref> NTUA was ranked between 551 and 600 by the [[QS World University Rankings]] in 2012, with the corresponding faculty area ranks being 152nd for [[Engineering & Technology]] and 352nd for [[Natural Sciences]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/node/2186/ranking-details/world-university-rankings/2012|title=QS Stars World University Rankings for NTUA|accessdate=2013-08-12}}</ref> The 2012 performance ranking of scientific papers for world universities released by the [[National Taiwan University]] (NTU Ranking) ranked NTUA as excellent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/announcements/elke/uploads/2012-10-10_142946_NTU_Ranking.pdf|title=NTU 2012 performance Ranking of Scientific Papers for World Universities - NTUA Ranking|accessdate=2013-08-09|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130903101700/http://www.ntua.gr/announcements/elke/uploads/2012-10-10_142946_NTU_Ranking.pdf|archivedate=2013-09-03}}</ref> NTUA has the highest citation impact score (0.88) among the Greek universities, based on a ranking prepared by the Directorate General for Science and Research of the [[European Commission]] in 2003 (updated 2004) that was compiled as part of the Third European Report on Science & Technology Indicators.<ref>{{cite web|url=ftp://ftp.cordis.europa.eu/pub/indicators/docs/3rd_report_snaps10.pdf|archive-url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20110709061451/ftp://ftp.cordis.europa.eu/pub/indicators/docs/3rd_report_snaps10.pdf |url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-07-09|title=Downsizing and Specializing: The university model for the 21st century?|accessdate=2013-08-12}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+[[QS World University Ranking]] for NTUA\n|+\n|-  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"75px\" | 2007\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"75px\" | 2008\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"75px\" | 2009\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"75px\" | 2010\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"75px\" | 2011\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"75px\" | 2012\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"75px\" | 2013\n! scope=\