\"50px\" | 2015\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"50px\" | 2016\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"50px\" | 2017\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"50px\" | 2018\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"50px\" | 2019\n|-\n! [[Engineering]] \n|  167 || 149 || 195 || 203 || 182 || 194 || 183 || 191 || 172 || 179 || 186 || 202\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n! colspan=10 | QS university subject rankings of NTUA<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.topuniversities.com/universities/national-technical-university-athens#sub |title= QS Stars NTUA University Subject Rankings for 2018|accessdate=2018-05-08}}</ref>\n|-\n! Subject !! 2011 !! 2012 !! 2013 !! 2014 !! 2015 !! 2016 !! 2017 !! 2018 !! 2019 !! 2020\n|-\n| Computer Science and Information Systems || 151-200 || 151-200  || 101-150  || 151-200 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150\n|-\n| Engineering - Chemical || 151-200 || 101-150  || 101-150  || 151-200 || 151-200 || 151-200 || 151-200 || 151-200 || 151-200 || 151-200\n|-\n| Engineering - Civil and Structural || 51-100 || 51-100 || 25  || 28 || 29 || 33 || 42 || 42 || 48 || 39\n|-\n| Engineering - Electrical and Electronic || 51-100 || 51-100 || 51-100  || 51-100 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 51-100 || 101-150 || 51-100\n|-\n| Engineering - Mechanical || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150  || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150\n|-\n| Mathematics || - || - || 151-200  || 151-200 || 201-250 || 201-250 || 251-300 || 251-300 || 301-350 || 201-250\n|-\n| Statistics and Operational Research || 101-150 || 151-200 || 51-100  || 101-150 || 101-150 || 151-200 || - || 151-200 || 151-200 || 151-200\n|-\n| Materials Science || - || - || -  || - || - || - || 201-250 || 251-300 || 251-300 || 301-350\n|-\n| Architecture || - || - || -  || - || - || - || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 51-100\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n! colspan=9 | NTU Subject Ranking for NTUA<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nturanking.lis.ntu.edu.tw/Default.aspx|title=NTU Ranking|accessdate=2013-11-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130830195354/http://nturanking.lis.ntu.edu.tw/Default.aspx|archive-date=2013-08-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n|-\n! Subject !! 2011 !! 2012 !! 2013 !! 2014 !! 2015 !! 2016 !! 2017 !! 2018 !! 2019\n|-\n| Computer Science || 127 || 152 || 180 || 195 || 201 || 163 || 163 || 211 || 212\n|-\n| Chemical Engineering || 78 || 95 || 88 || 91 || 118 || 114 || 97 || 83 || 90\n|-\n| Civil Engineering || 87 || 64 || 72 || 70 || 53 || 64 || 72 || 82 || 107\n|-\n| Mechanical Engineering || 77 || 79 || 77 || 53 || 65 || 61 || 57 || 58 || 59\n|}\n\n==Campus==\n\n===Patision Complex===\n[[File:NTUA Patision library.jpg|thumb|260px|NTUA School of Architecture Library at the Patision Complex]]\nThe Averof building is one of the most important and elegant buildings of the Athenian Neoclassical period located in the center of [[Athens]] and the most important work of architect [[Lysandros Kaftanzoglou]]. It constitutes also one of the most important creations of European [[Neoclassicism]], directly influenced in its design by the monuments of the Athenian [[Acropolis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europanostra.org/awards/69/|title=Europa Nostra - The conservation project of the Averof Building|accessdate=2013-08-11}}</ref> Its construction began in 1862 and ended in 1878. After its completion, the building was in continuous use for more than 125 years during which it suffered from several additions and alterations. The main building has housed at times the [[National Gallery (Athens)|National Gallery]] and various exhibitions of [[Heinrich Schliemann|Schliemann]]'s archaeological findings and relics of the 1821 [[Greek revolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arch.ntua.gr/page/28|title=NTUA Architecture School - The Averof Building|accessdate=2013-08-11}}</ref>\n\nThe Averof building reached a deteriorating state and was eventually in great need of restoration and modernization in order to continue operating as an educational establishment. The aim of the conservation project, namely for the Averof to be used again as an educational building, was successfully achieved after the building became operative in the beginning of 2010 and won the grand prize of [[Europa Nostra]] in 2012.\n\n\n===Zografou Campus===\n[[File:Attica 06-13 Hills of Hymettus 15 view.jpg|right|thumb|260px|View of the Zografou campus from Kalogeros hill]]\nThe main campus is located in the [[Zografou]] area of [[Athens]], housing all the schools of NTUA except architecture, which remains in its traditional location on the [[Patision Avenue]] for historical reasons. The main campus spreads over an area of about 190 acres,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://map.ntua.gr/google.htm|title=NTUA Digital Map|accessdate=2010-09-21|publisher=NTUA}}</ref> 6&nbsp;km from the center of [[Athens]]. It includes buildings of 65 acres with fully equipped lecture theaters, laboratories, libraries, gyms, a central library, a computer center and a medical center.\n\nThe School of Applied Mathematics and Physical Sciences is housed in the center of the campus. Right next to it is the Mining and Metallurgical Engineering School. The Civil Engineering School and the Rural and Surveying Engineering School are both housed on the south-west near the Zografou Gate. Mechanical Engineering, Chemical Engineering, Naval Engineering, and the new Electrical Engineering School are all housed near the middle of the campus, while the old electrical engineering buildings remain on the north-east.\n\n====Transportation====\nThere are in-campus roads making all buildings accessible by bicycle and car. There are also various internal buses that allow for transportation within the facilities, driving around the perimeter of the campus and through eight different bus stops. The campus is accessible through three main gates: the [[Katechaki Avenue|Katechaki]] and Kokkinopoulou Gates on the north, and the Zografou Gate on the west. There are 2,000 dedicated parking spots scattered throughout the campus, most nearby all major buildings. The campus resides near the [[Katehaki station|metro station of Katechaki]], which makes it accessible within minutes from any area of Athens. Furthermore, six different buses are available for transportation from various city locations to the campus: the 608 from [[Galatsi]], 230 from [[Acropolis]], 242 from the Katechaki Metro station and 140 from [[Glifada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/visit.html|accessdate=2010-09-21|publisher=NTUA|title=Transportation at NTUA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716094615/http://www.ntua.gr/visit.html|archivedate=2011-07-16}}</ref>\n\n====Central Library====\n[[File:Ntua library.jpg|thumb|Central Library of National Technical University of Athens]]\nOn the campus lies the NTUA Central [[Library]], which has operated since 1914, and was the first library in [[Greece]] with a complete index. Today, it remains one of the largest technical libraries in the country, featuring a collection of over 215,000 books and 100,000 scientific issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.ntua.gr/newsite/el/ghistory.htm|title=History of the NTUA Library|accessdate=2010-09-21|publisher=NTUA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721082646/http://www.lib.ntua.gr/newsite/el/ghistory.htm|archivedate=2011-07-21}}</ref> The library is available to the public at all times for studying, and available to students, faculty, and internal and external researchers for borrowing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.ntua.gr/newsite/el/gborFAQ.htm|title=NTUA Library FAQ|accessdate=2010-09-21|publisher=NTUA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100824085333/http://www.lib.ntua.gr/newsite/el/gborFAQ.htm|archivedate=2010-08-24}}</ref>\n\nThe central library building at Zografou campus houses also the historical library of NTUA as a special collection. This scientific-technical library is unique in Greece, and one of the most important in Europe, since it contains approximately 60,000 volumes and periodicals (1,096 titles) issued from the 17th century until 1950.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.ntua.gr/gr/info/closed_collection.html|title=Special collections of NTUA Library|accessdate=2013-08-09|publisher=NTUA}}</ref> The main bulk of NTUA's historical collection consists of old and rare books, pamphlets, maps, engravings and encyclopedias.\n\n===Other facilities===\n\n====Lavrion Technological and Cultural Park (LTCP)====\nLavrion Technological and Cultural Park (LTCP),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ltp.ntua.gr/home_en|title=NTUA Lavrion Technological and Cultural Park (LTCP)|accessdate=2013-08-10|publisher=NTUA}}</ref> is a body of scientific research, education, business and culture. Founded in place of the old French Mining Company of Lavrion (Compagnie Francaise des Mines du [[Laurium]]) in 1992, as a result of the initiative undertaken from the National Technical University of Athens.\n\nLTCP aims at linking scientific and technological research conducted in Athens with the needs and interests of the business world, and to the realization of cultural events related to the promotion of the history and culture of the wider area of Lavreotiki, and the emergence of the history of activities in the past had developed in the maintenance of premises. The LTCP area is a unique monument of industrial architecture and archeology and placed him in a series of housing facilities for business and research excellence.\n\nThe services provided by LTCP as well as its renovated facilities, continue to support research, education and technology. Today, LTCP is essentially the only technology park in Attica, which specializes in areas - keys of modern applied technology, such as information technology, electronics technology, telecommunications, robotics, technology laser, environmental technology, energy, shipbuilding, marine technology, etc.\n\n====Metsovion Interdisciplinary Research Center (MIRC)====\n[[File:MIRC NTUA.jpg|thumb|MIRC facilities at [[Metsovo]]]]\nThe Metsovion Interdisciplinary Research Center (MIRC) of the National Technical University of Athens for the Protection and Development of Mountainous Environment and Local European Cultures was founded in 1993 by decision of the National Technical University of Athens Senate, following the proposal of the then [[Rector (academia)|Rector]] Professor [[Nikos Markatos]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/MIRC/mekde/mekde-gb.html|title=NTUA Metsovion Interdisciplinary Research Center (MIRC)|accessdate=2013-08-10|publisher=NTUA}}</ref>\n\nThe principal aim of MIRC is to contribute to the protection and development of mountainous environment and local European cultures and the provision of [[continuing education]]. As well as, the conduct of [[research]], studies, [[seminars]] and [[Academic conference|conferences]], relevant to the broader object of MIRC, the creation of a European network with related organizations under the aegis of the center or the participation in already existing networks. The above will be utilized by universities, cultural, research and productive organizations with the aim of assisting [[Metsovon]] in becoming a European center of decentralized interdisciplinary, educational, research, technological and cultural activities of NTUA.\n\n==Culture==\n{{listen\n|filename=NTUA_Choir_-_Lemonaki.ogg\n|title=NTUA Choir&nbsp;\u2013 Lemonaki\n|description=The NTUA choir performing the folk greek song \"Lemonaki\" in a mixed choir rearrangement in 2010\n|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n===Music Department===\nThe NTUA Music Department was established in 1960 by Chancellor Alexander Pappas. The first president of the music department was composer Vassilis Makridis. It features a [[mixed choir]], a [[string orchestra]], and free lessons for various instruments, among others [[piano]], [[guitar]], [[bouzouki]], and [[cello]]. The music department groups regularly perform publicly within the facilities of the university, but also elsewhere. The department president today is [[Conducting|conductor]] and [[composer]] Michalis Economou.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/old/gr_culture/music/music.htm|title=NTUA Music department|publisher=NTUA|accessdate=2010-09-21|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821085746/http://www.ntua.gr/old/gr_culture/music/music.htm|archivedate=2010-08-21}}</ref>\n\n===Dancing Department===\nThe Dancing Department was established in 1990. It is formed by students, and it features various groups, including a Greek traditional and Cretan [[folk dances]] group, a European and [[Latin]] Ballroom dances group, a Salsa and a [[tango]] group. The groups meets weekly, and perform regularly inside and outside the facilities of the university. Attendance and dancing lessons are free for undergraduate and graduate students, alumni, faculty and even people not related to the University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dance.ntua.gr/files/aitisi_eggrafis_17.pdf|title=Dance Club NTUA|last=|first=|date=|website=dance.ntua.gr|access-date=}}</ref> The dancing department is housed near the center of the main campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dance.ntua.gr/|accessdate=2010-09-21|title=Dancing department of NTUA|publisher=NTUA Dancing department}}</ref>\n\n===Theatrical Group===\nThe Theatrical Group was established in 1991. It is a self-managed group, which teaches the art of performance and often performs in public. Participation in the group is free for students. The theatrical group is housed near the center of the main campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/theatre/cv.shtml|title=Theatrical Group History|accessdate=2010-09-21|publisher=NTUA Theatrical Group}}</ref> The theatrical group has also organized a separate percussion lessons group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/theatre/percussion.shtml|title=Percussion Seminar|accessdate=2010-09-21|publisher=NTUA Theatrical Group}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nThe main sports facilities of NTUA are housed in the Sports Center located to the south of the campus, taking up about 3,500 square meters. The campus sport facilities feature [[tennis]] and [[soccer]] courts, a field and track, a [[sauna]], [[ping pong]] tables, and more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://map.ntua.gr/google.htm|accessdate=2010-09-21|title=NTUA Map|publisher=NTUA}}</ref> More than 40 sport teams exist, and the sports practiced include [[aerobic exercise|aerobics]], [[yoga]], [[Pilates]], [[basketball]], [[volleyball]], [[soccer]], [[handball]], [[ping pong]], [[tennis]], [[martial arts]] inside the campus facilities and [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[polo]], [[rowing (sport)|rowing]], [[yachting]], [[rappelling]], [[rafting]], [[Squash (sport)|squash]], [[wind surfing]], and [[equestrianism]] outside.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/announcements/dty/uploads/2009-11-02_348730_invitation.pdf|accessdate=2010-09-21|title=NTUA Sport Center Opening Ceremony|publisher=NTUA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821192746/http://www.ntua.gr/announcements/dty/uploads/2009-11-02_348730_invitation.pdf|archivedate=2010-08-21}}</ref>\n\nEach year several inter-departmental championships are organized among the teams of the university faculties. NTUA student's teams have been distinguished and received many awards in Panhellenic University Games, as well as in university games abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/old/en_academics/stud_services.htm#three|accessdate=2010-09-21|title=NTUA Sporting Activities|publisher=NTUA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100731073144/http://www.ntua.gr/old/en_academics/stud_services.htm#three|archivedate=2010-07-31}}</ref>\n\n===Open source===\nThere is an open source students group whose purpose is to promote the use of [[open source software]] throughout the university and beyond.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://foss.ntua.gr/wiki/index.php/%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%B9%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%84%CE%B7%CF%84%CE%B1_%CE%95%CE%BB%CE%B5%CF%8D%CE%B8%CE%B5%CF%81%CE%BF%CF%85_%CE%9B%CE%BF%CE%B3%CE%B9%CF%83%CE%BC%CE%B9%CE%BA%CE%BF%CF%8D_%CE%95%CE%9C%CE%A0|accessdate=2010-09-22|title=Open Source Software Community of NTUA|publisher=Open Source Software Community of NTUA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125070903/http://foss.ntua.gr/wiki/index.php/%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%B9%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%84%CE%B7%CF%84%CE%B1_%CE%95%CE%BB%CE%B5%CF%8D%CE%B8%CE%B5%CF%81%CE%BF%CF%85_%CE%9B%CE%BF%CE%B3%CE%B9%CF%83%CE%BC%CE%B9%CE%BA%CE%BF%CF%8D_%CE%95%CE%9C%CE%A0|archive-date=2010-11-25|url-status=dead}}</ref> Furthermore, NTUA officially supports open source software by using it in its laboratories and other facilities, but also hosting mirrors for all major open source projects <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noc.ntua.gr/index.php?module=ContentExpress&func=display&ceid=35|accessdate=2010-09-22|title=FTP mirrors|publisher=NTUA NOC}}</ref> with a collection of over 2.5 [[terabyte]]s of free and open source software.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftp.ntua.gr/|accessdate=2010-09-22|title=FTP.NTUA.GR|publisher=NTUA}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign languages===\n[[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]] and [[Italian language|Italian]] are the four languages taught in NTUA. All non-exchange students have to choose one from those as a mandatory foreign language course. For foreign students the NTUA Linguistic Service offers the option of attending Greek courses during the entire [[academic year]], free of charge. These courses are intended to provide students with the basic linguistic tools, so that they can understand and communicate efficiently with people in Greece.\n\n==Participation in international organizations==\n* [http://www.cesaer.org CESAER \u2013 Conference of European Schools for advanced Engineering, Education and Research]\n* [http://www.top.upv.es/eegecs/main.asp [[EEGECS]] - Network on European Education in Geodetic Engineering, Cartography and Surveying]\n* [http://www.sefi.be SEFI \u2013 Societe Europeene pour la Formation des Ingenieurs (European Society for Engineering Education)]\n* [https://www.time-association.org TIME \u2013 Top Industrial Managers Europe]\n\n===Student unions===\n* [http://www.fsae.ntua.gr/  NTUA Students' Formula Team]\n* [http://www.mindspace.gr/ Mindspace], an association to promote innovation and entrepreneurship among students\n* Society of Naval Architects and Marine Engineers, NTUA\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130711041522/http://www.ntua.gr/best/athens/#!/Gallery  Athens Local BEST Group]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130902130921/http://eestec.ntua.gr/eestec/en/ Electrical Engineering STudent's European Association Local Committee of Athens (EESTEC)]\n* [http://euroavia.ntua.gr/wordpress/?lang=en Euroavia Athens, NTUA]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130807143141/http://www.ntua.gr/iaeste/ International Association for the Exchange of Students for Technical Experience (IAESTE)]\n*American Institute of Chemical Engineers Student Chapter (AIChE)\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Alexis Tsipras]] - former [[Prime Minister of Greece]]\n* [[Nicholas Ambraseys]] - professor of engineering seismology at [[Imperial College London]]\n* [[Dimitris Anastassiou]] - developer of [[MPEG-2]] algorithm for transmitting high quality audio and video over limited bandwidth and [[Columbia University]] professor of electrical engineering\n* [[John Argyris]] - one of the founders of the [[finite element method]], professor at [[Imperial College London]] and [[University of Stuttgart]]\n* [[Dimitri Bertsekas]] - professor of engineering at [[MIT]]\n* [[Costas Azariadis]] - professor at the Department of Economics, UCLA and Edward Mallinckrodt Distinguished University Professor in Arts & Sciences, Washington University in St. Louis\n* [[Georges Candilis]] - architect and urbanist, one of the founders of [[Team 10]]\n* [[Giorgio de Chirico]] - painter\n* [[Constantine Dafermos]] - Greek applied mathematician, professor at [[Brown University]] and recipient of [[Norbert Wiener Prize in Applied Mathematics]]\n* [[Constantinos Daskalakis]] - computer scientist, professor at [[MIT]]\n* [[Athos Dimoulas]] - poet\n* [[Georgios Gennimatas]] - former MP, minister and founding member of  [[Panhellenic Socialist Movement]]\n* [[John Iliopoulos]] - recipient of the [[Dirac Medal]]\n* [[Paris Kanellakis]] - computer scientist, professor at [[Brown University]]\n* [[Linda P. B. Katehi]] - Chancellor of [[UC Davis]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wascsenior.org/commission/commissioner/linda-katehi|title=Linda Katehi &#124; Senior College and University Commission|accessdate=2014-11-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406013715/http://www.wascsenior.org/commission/commissioner/linda-katehi|archivedate=2015-04-06}}</ref>\n* [[Nikos Markatos]] - former Rector of the NTUA\n* [[Constantine Papadakis]] - former president of [[Drexel University]]\n* [[Christos Papadimitriou]] - computer scientist, laureate of the 2002 [[Knuth Prize]] for longstanding and seminal contributions to the foundations of computer science\n* [[Yannis Papathanasiou]] - politician, former [[Minister for Economy and Finance of Greece]]\n* [[Nicholas A. Peppas]] - professor in engineering, [[University of Texas at Austin]]\n* [[Dimitris Pikionis]] - architect\n* [[George Prokopiou]] - billionaire shipowner<ref name=BloombergProfile>{{cite web|title=George Prokopiou|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profiles/people/18345260-george-prokopiou|website=Bloomberg|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Charalambos Bouras]] - historian, professor of History of Architecture and restoration architect\n* [[Athanasios Roussopoulos]] - professor in applied statics and iron constructions at the National Technical University of Athens, where his work was mostly concerned with the development of the theory of aseismic structures, politician, member of the [[Greek Parliament]] and [[Minister of Public Works]] in 1966, he was also president of the [[Technical Chamber of Greece]]\n* [[Joseph Sifakis]] - computer scientist, laureate of the 2007 [[Turing Award]] for his work on [[model checking]].\n* [[Michael Triantafyllou]] - professor of mechanical and ocean engineering at [[MIT]]\n* [[Ioannis Vardoulakis]] - professor of civil engineering at [[University of Minnesota]] and at NTUA, a pioneer of theoretical and experimental geomechanics\n* [[Iannis Xenakis]] - one of the most important post-war avant-garde composers, pioneer of the use of mathematical models in music and architect\n* [[Mihalis Yannakakis]] - computer scientist, laureate of the 2005 [[Knuth Prize]] for numerous ground-breaking contributions to theoretical computer science\n* [[Mihail Zervos]] - professor of financial mathematics at [[London School of Economics]]\n* Theodosios Tasios - professor of NTUA, author, civil engineer\n*[[Emmanouil Korres]] - professor, writer, restoration architect\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Constantine Papadakis.jpg|President of Drexel University [[Constantine Papadakis]], Civil '69\nFile:Christos Papadimitriou mg 7721-b.cr2.jpg|''Computational Complexity'' author [[Christos Papadimitriou]], ECE '72\nFile:Nicholas A Peppas 1-12-08.jpg|[[Nicholas A. Peppas]], Chemical '71\nFile:Mihalis Yannakakis 2006.jpg|Knuth Prize 2005 winner [[Mihalis Yannakakis]], ECE '75\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Athens Polytechnic uprising]]\n* [[Polytechnic (Greece)]]\n* [[List of universities in Greece]]\n* [[Top Industrial Managers for Europe]]\n* [[Open access in Greece]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|National Technical University of Athens}}\n* [http://www.adip.gr/ Hellenic Quality Assurance and Accreditation Agency (HQAA)] {{in lang|el|en}}\n** [http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_NavalArchMarineEng_%202012.pdf School of Naval Architecture and Marine Engineering, HQAA Final Report, 2012] \n** [http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_MechEng_2012.pdf School of Mechanical Engineering, HQAA Final Report, 2012] \n** [http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_CivilEng_2013.pdf School of Civil Engineering, HQAA Final Report, 2013] \n** [http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_ElecCompEng_2013.pdf School of Electrical and Computer Engineering, HQAA Final Report, 2013]\n** [http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_ApplMathPhysical_2013.pdf School of Applied Mathematical & Physical Science, HQAA Final Report, 2013]\n** [http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_ChemEng_2013.pdf School of Chemical Engineering, HQAA Final Report, 2013]\n** [http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_RuralSurveyingEng_2013.pdf School of Rural & Surveying Engineering, HQAA Final Report, 2013]\n** [http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_MiningMetalEng_2013.pdf School of Mining & Metallurgical Engineering, HQAA Final Report, 2013]\n** [http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_Architecture_2014.pdf School of Architecture, HQAA Final Report, 2014]\n* [http://si.ntua.gr/ NTUA Council] {{in lang|el}}  \n* [http://www.minedu.gov.gr/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=9325 \"ATHENA\" Plan for Higher Education, 2013] {{in lang|el}}\n* [http://www.ntua.gr/ National Technical University of Athens (NTUA) - Official Website] {{in lang|el|en}}\n* [http://www.lib.ntua.gr/ NTUA Central Library]\n* [http://www.noc.ntua.gr/ NTUA Network Management Center (NOC)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140203135604/http://dasta.ntua.gr/dasta/index.php/en/ NTUA DASTA Office (Career Office & Innovation Unit)] {{in lang|el|en}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140203135602/http://dasta.ntua.gr/coop-en/ NTUA Internship Programme] {{in lang|el|en}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130627152739/http://mke.ntua.gr/home NTUA Innovation and Entrepreneurship Unit (IEU)]  {{in lang|el}}\n* [http://erasmus.ntua.gr/ NTUA ERASMUS Office]\n* [http://map.ntua.gr/ Maps and images from NTUA's campuses.]\n* [http://press.ntua.gr/english.html NTUA Publications]\n* [http://career.central.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=77&Itemid=107 NTUA Career Office]\n* [http://ntua.esngreece.gr ESN NTUA Athens]\n* [http://www.ltp.ntua.gr/home_en/ Lavrion Technological and Cultural Park (LTCP) of NTUA]\n* [http://www.ntua.gr/MIRC/ Metsovion Interdisciplinary Research Center (MIRC) of NTUA]\n* [http://hoa.ntua.gr/ NTUA Hydrological Observatory of Athens]\n* [https://www.grnet.gr/en Greek Research & Technology Network (GRNET)] {{in lang|el|en}}\n* [https://okeanos.grnet.gr/home/ okeanos (GRNET's cloud service)] {{in lang|el|en}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070801175205/http://foss.ntua.gr/wiki/index.php/%CE%91%CF%81%CF%87%CE%B9%CE%BA%CE%AE_%CF%83%CE%B5%CE%BB%CE%AF%CE%B4%CE%B1 NTUA Free and Open Source Community]\n* [http://ieee.ntua.gr/ieee/ IEEE NTUA Student Branch] {{in lang|el|en}}\n* [http://www.jobfairathens.gr/ Job Fair Athens] {{in lang|el|en}}\n* [http://www.synodos-aei.gr/index_en.html Hellenic Universities Rectors' Synod] {{in lang|el|en}}\n* [http://www.posdep.gr/ Hellenic Universities Faculty Association] {{in lang|el}}\n\n{{Greek Universities}}\n{{Top Industrial Managers for Europe|State=collapsed}}\n{{CESAER}}\n\n{{coord|37|59|16.31|N|23|43|53.81|E|dim:100_scale:1000_region:GR_type:landmark_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:National Technical University of Athens|*]]\n[[Category:Universities in Greece]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1837]]\n[[Category:Technical universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Greece]]\n[[Category:Education in Athens]]\n[[Category:National Technical University of Athens alumni| ]]\n[[Category:Engineering universities and colleges in Greece]]\n[[Category:1837 establishments in Greece]]\n[[Category:Exarcheia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Hatnote|NTUA redirects here. For the Taiwanese university, see [[National Taiwan University of Arts]].}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name         = National (Metsovian) Technical University of Athens\n| native_name  = \u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039c\u03b5\u03c4\u03c3\u03cc\u03b2\u03b9\u03bf \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\n| latin_name   = \n| motto        = \n| image        = Pyrforos2.png\n| caption      = Seal of NTUA\n| established  = December 31, 1836 {{small|[[Adoption of the Gregorian calendar#Adoption in Eastern Europe|(OS)]]}}<br />  January 21, 1837 {{small|(NS)}}<ref name=\"Ntua History Greek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/history2.html|script-title=el:\u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1|publisher=NTUA.gr|language=Greek|accessdate=2009-03-30|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502181741/http://www.ntua.gr/history2.html|archivedate=2012-05-02}}</ref>\n| type         = [[Public university|Public]]<br />[[Higher education|Higher Education Institution]]<br />[[List of universities in Greece|Greece University System]]\n| endowment    = \n| staff        = 1350<ref name=\"NTUA Schools\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/schools_en.html|title=NTUA Schools|publisher=NTUA.gr|accessdate=2009-01-28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090129180735/http://www.ntua.gr/schools_en.html|archivedate=2009-01-29}}</ref>\n| faculty      = \n| president    = \n| provost      = \n| principal    = \n| rector       = Andreas Boudouvis<ref>https://www.ntua.gr/en/ntua/members-and-administrator</ref>\n| dean         = \n| head_label   = \n| head         = \n| students     = \n| undergrad    = 8500<ref name=\"NTUA Schools\"/>\n| postgrad     = 1500<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/postgraduate_en.html|title=Postgraduate Studies|publisher=NTUA.gr|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915094042/http://www.ntua.gr/postgraduate_en.html|archivedate=2014-09-15}}</ref>\n| doctoral     = \n| city         = [[Athens]]\n| state        = \n| country      = [[Greece]]\n| campus       = [[Patission Avenue|Patision]] Complex <br/> <small>''(central [[Athens]])''</small>, <br/> [[Zografou]] campus <br/> <small>''([[Central Athens]] district)''</small><ref name=\"General Information\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/contact_en.html|title=General Information|publisher=NTUA.gr|accessdate=2009-01-28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120701103003/http://www.ntua.gr/contact_en.html|archivedate=2012-07-01}}</ref>\n| free_label   = Also known as\n| free         = Athens Polytechnic <br />National Metsovian Polytechnic\n| colors       = [[White]] and [[Gold (color)|Gold]] {{Color box|#ffffff|border=darkgray}}{{Color box|#f1b93e|border=darkgray}}\n| colours      = \n| mascot       = [[Prometheus]]\n| nickname     = \n| affiliations = [[Top Industrial Managers for Europe|TIME]], [[CESAER Association|CESAER]]\n| website      = {{url|www.ntua.gr}}\n| athletics    = 40 sports\n| logo         = \n}}\n\nThe '''National''' ('''Metsovian''') '''Technical University of Athens''' ('''NTUA'''; {{lang-el|\u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039c\u03b5\u03c4\u03c3\u03cc\u03b2\u03b9\u03bf \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03bf}}, ''National Metsovian Polytechnic''), sometimes known as '''Athens Polytechnic''', is among the oldest higher education institutions of [[Greece]] and the most prestigious among engineering schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2016|date=January 1, 2016|accessdate=2016-11-29|title=QS World University Rankings 2016-2017}}</ref> It is named ''Metsovio(n)'' in honor of its benefactors Nikolaos Stournaris, Eleni Tositsa, Michail Tositsas and Georgios Averoff, whose origin is from the town of [[Metsovo]] in [[Epirus (region)|Epirus]].<ref name=\"NTUA History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/history_en.html|title=History|publisher=NTUA.gr|accessdate=2009-03-30|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090401190941/http://www.ntua.gr/history_en.html|archivedate=2009-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIt was founded in 1837 as a part-time vocational school named '''Royal School of Arts''' which, as its role in the technical development of the fledgling state grew, developed into Greece's sole institution providing engineering degrees up until the 1950s, when polytechnics were established outiside [[Athens]]. Its traditional [[campus]], located in the center of Athens on [[Patision Avenue]], features a suite of magnificent neo-[[classical architecture|classical]] buildings by architect Lysandros Kaftantzoglou (1811\u20131885). A new campus, the [[Zografou]] Campus, was built in the 1980s.<ref name=\"NTUA History\" />\n\nNTUA is divided into nine academic schools, eight being for the [[engineering]] disciplines, including [[architecture]], and one for applied [[sciences]] (mathematics and physics). Undergraduate studies have a duration of five years. Admission to NTUA is highly selective and can only be accomplished through achieving exceptional grades in the annual [[Panhellenic Examinations|Panhellenic Exams]]. It is a widely spread perception that the vast majority of each year's Panhellenic Exams top students interested in the sciences and technology opts to attend NTUA. The university comprises about 700 of academic staff, 140 scientific assistants and 260 administrative and technical staff. It also has about 8,500 undergraduates and about 1,500 postgraduate students.<ref name=\"NTUA Schools\" /> Eight of the NTUA's Schools are housed at the Zografou Campus, while the School of Architecture is based at the Patision Complex.\n\n==History==\nNTUA was established by [[Kingdom of Greece (Wittelsbach)|royal]] decree on December 31, 1836 [[Adoption of the Gregorian calendar#Adoption in Eastern Europe|(OS)]], January 21, 1837 (NS), under the name  \"Royal School of Arts\" (\u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03a3\u03c7\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bf \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03a4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd).<ref name=\"Ntua History Greek\" /> It began functioning as a part-time vocational school (only Sundays and holidays) to train craftsmen, builders and master craftsmen to cover the needs of the [[History of modern Greece|new Greek state]]. In 1840, due to its increasing popularity and the changing socio-economic conditions in the new state, NTUA was upgraded to a daily technical school which worked along with the Sunday school. The courses were expanded and the institution was housed in its own building in [[Pireos Street]].<ref name=\"Ntua History Greek\" />\n\n===The restructuring===\nIn 1843 a major restructuring was made. Three departments were created:\n\n* ''Part-Time Vocational School''\n* ''Daily School''\n* A new ''Higher School of Fine Arts''\n\nThe new department's object was fine arts and engineering. The new department, which was later renamed ''School of Industrial and Fine Arts'', rapidly evolved towards a major higher education institution. Tradition has it that ''arts'' referred to both technical professions and fine arts. Even today, the school maintains a school of architecture that is closely related to the School of Fine Arts, which later evolved to become a separate school.\n\nThe name ''Polytechnnic'' came in 1862, with the introduction of several new technical courses. This restructuring continued steadily until 1873. At the time, the school became overwhelmed by the plethora of students wanting to learn high technical skills, and this led to its moving to a new campus.\n\n===The relocation===\n[[File:NTUA - Patision Complex.jpg|right|thumb|340px|The historical Patision Street campus in a postcard of 1900.]]\n[[File:NTUA Averof Building Main Facade.jpg|thumb|240px|The main facade of the Averof building today.]]\n\nIn 1873 it moved to its new campus in [[Patision Street]] and was known as ''Metsovion Polytechnion'' (Metsovian Polytechnic) after the birthplace of its benefactors who financed the construction of this campus. At the time, the campus in Patision Street was even partially incomplete, but the high demand by students made it urgent to rellocate.\n\nIn 1887, the institution was partitioned into three schools of technical orientation, the schools of Structural Engineering, Architecture and Mechanical Engineering, all four-year degrees at the time. This is when the institute was recognized as a technical education facility by the state, which was a crucial step for its development, as it became accompanied to the country's needs as it developed.\n\nIn 1914, new schools were created and was officially named ''Ethnicon Metsovion Polytechnion'' (National Metsovian Polytechnic) went under the supervision of the Ministry of Public Works. This is when new technical schools started to be formed, a procedure was completed three years later, in 1917 when the NTUA changed form: By special law, the old ''School of Industrial Arts'' was now separated into the Higher Schools of ''Civil Engineering'', ''Mechanical&nbsp;&amp; Electrical Engineering'', ''Chemical Engineering'', ''Surveying Engineering'' and ''Architecture''. Later, the schools of ''Naval Engineering'', and ''Mining and Metallurgical Engineering'' were formed, and the school of ''Mechanical&nbsp;&amp; Electrical Engineering'' was split up into two separate schools, ''Mechanical Engineering'' and ''Electrical and Computer Engineering'', which is almost the form of schools maintained until now.\n\nIn 1923, the NTUA alumni formed the core of the [[Technical Chamber of Greece]], the professional organization that serves as the official technical adviser of the [[Greek state]] and is responsible for awarding professional licenses to all practicing engineers in Greece.<ref name=\"NTUA History\" />\n\nIn 1930, the [[Athens School of Fine Arts]] was established, acquiring its independence from the NTUA, as a school exclusively focused in the teaching the fine arts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asfa.gr/greek/ASKT/info/info01.htm|date=September 20, 2010|accessdate=2010-09-20|title=\u0391\u03bd\u03ce\u03c4\u03b1\u03c4\u03b7 \u03a3\u03c7\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae \u039a\u03b1\u03bb\u03ce\u03bd \u03a4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd&nbsp;\u2013 \u038a\u03b4\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03b7 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03a3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03cc\u03c2}}</ref> This allowed the two schools to develop separately as a technical and an arts school respectively.\n\nIn 1941 to 1944, the National Technical University of Athens played an important role in the country's political life with the Greek students participating in the [[Greek Resistance|National Resistance]] under the German occupation. During the [[Axis occupation of Greece during World War II|Axis occupation of Greece]], NTUA, in addition to its function as an academic institution, became one of the most active [[Greek Resistance#Resistance in the cities|resistance]] centers in Athens.\n\n===The uprising===\n{{main|Athens Polytechnic uprising}}\nThe most important event of NTUA's history is the [[Athens Polytechnic uprising]] on November 17, 1973, which was the first step to overthrow [[Greek military junta of 1967-1974|Greece's military dictatorship]].\nOn 14, 15 and 16 of November 1973, the students were barricaded inside the institute, and started broadcasting a pirate radio transmission, calling the people of Athens to rebel. In the evening of November 17 however, an AMX-30 class military tank broke the main gate and charged inside, after receiving orders from the dictators. About 23 people were killed in the following events and the uprising ended. The junta however, was irreparably damaged by the popular outcry. The junta fell in 1974, after the Turkish invasion in Cyprus and since then, November 17 is celebrated as a day of freedom and democracy. All schools and universities of the country remain closed on that day.<ref name=\"NTUA History\" />\n\n==Emblem==\nThe emblem of the National Technical University of Athens is [[Prometheus]].\n\n==Academic profile==\n\n===Schools===\nThe National Technical University of Athens is divided into nine academic schools ({{lang-el|\u03c3\u03c7\u03bf\u03bb\u03ad\u03c2}}), which are furthermore divided into 33 departments (Greek: \u03c4\u03bf\u03bc\u03b5\u03af\u03c2):<ref name=\"NTUA Schools\"/>\n\n*School of [[Applied Mathematics]] and [[Physics]]\n*School of [[Electrical and Computer Engineering]]\n*School of [[Civil Engineering]]\n*School of [[Mechanical Engineering]]\n*School of [[Architecture]]\n*School of [[Chemical Engineering]]\n*School of Rural and [[Surveying Engineering]]\n*School of Mining and [[Metallurgical Engineering]]\n*School of [[Naval Architecture]] and [[Marine Engineering]]\n{{hidden begin|border=solid 1px #aaa|title={{center|Departments by School}}}} \n* [http://semfe.ntua.gr '''School of [[Applied Mathematics]] and [[Physics]]''']\n** [http://www.math.ntua.gr/en_index.html Department of [[Mathematics]]]\n** [http://www.physics.ntua.gr Department of [[Physics]]]\n**[https://web.archive.org/web/20070526223207/http://www.mechan.ntua.gr/en/index.html Department of Mechanics]\n** [http://www.aked.ntua.gr Department of Humanities, Social Sciences and Law]\n* [http://www.ece.ntua.gr '''School of Electrical and Computer Engineering''']\n** [http://www.ece.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_divisions&task=division&id=3&Itemid=60&lang=en Department of Signals, Controls and Robotics]\n** [http://www.ece.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_divisions&task=division&id=4&Itemid=60&lang=en Department of Computer Science]\n** [http://www.ece.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_divisions&task=division&id=6&Itemid=60&lang=en Department of \u0395lectric Power]\n** [http://www.ece.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_divisions&task=division&id=1&Itemid=60&lang=en Department of Electromagnetics, Electrooptics and Electronic Materials]\n** [http://www.ece.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_divisions&task=division&id=7&Itemid=60&lang=en Department of Industrial Electric Devices and Decision Systems]\n** [http://www.ece.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_divisions&task=division&id=5&Itemid=60&lang=en Department of Communications, Electronics and Information Systems]\n** [http://www.ece.ntua.gr/index.php?option=com_divisions&task=division&id=2&Itemid=60&lang=en Department of Information Transmission Systems and Material Technology]\n* [http://www.civil.ntua.gr '''School of Civil Engineering''']\n** [https://archive.today/20070619083625/http://www.civil.ntua.gr/new/htdocs/main.php?show=isaar&lang=en Department of Structural Engineering]\n** [http://www.hydro.ntua.gr Department of Water Resources, Hydraulic and Maritime Engineering]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20060418003622/http://www.civil.ntua.gr/new/htdocs/main.php?show=traffic&lang=en Department of Transportation Planning and Engineering]\n** [http://www.civil.ntua.gr/geotech/index.php?lang=en Department of Geotechnical Engineering]\n** [http://cem.civil.ntua.gr/ Department of Engineering Construction and Management]\n[[File:NTUA mechanical engineers school.jpg|right|thumb|240px|View of the School of Mechanical Engineering.]]\n* [http://www.mech.ntua.gr/en'''School of Mechanical Engineering''']\n** [http://fluid.ntua.gr Department of Fluid Mechanics Engineering]\n** Department of Thermal Engineering\n** [http://nuclear.ntua.gr Department of Nuclear Engineering]\n** [http://csl.mech.ntua.gr Department of Mechanical Constructions and Automatic Control]\n** [http://www.mech.ntua.gr/en/sections/TTK Department of Manufacturing Technology]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20130728153211/http://www.mech.ntua.gr/en/sections/TBD_EE Department of Industrial Management and Operational Research]\n* [http://www.arch.ntua.gr '''School of Architecture''']\n** Department of Architectural Design\n** Department of Urban and Regional Planning\n** Department of Interior Design and Landscaping\n** Department of Building Technology-Structural Design and Mechanical Equipment\n* [http://www.chemeng.ntua.gr '''School of Chemical Engineering''']\n** Department of Chemical Sciences\n** [http://www.chemeng.ntua.gr/main.php?tomeas2 Department of Process and Systems Analysis, Design and Development]\n** Department of Materials Science and Engineering\n** Department of Synthesis and Development of Industrial Processes\n* [http://www.survey.ntua.gr/en '''School of Rural and Surveying Engineering''']\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20141027084228/http://www.survey.ntua.gr/en/departments/topo.html Department of Topography]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20141027084143/http://www.survey.ntua.gr/en/departments/geo.html Department of Geography and Regional Planning]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20141027084128/http://www.survey.ntua.gr/en/departments/infrastructure.html Department of Infrastructure and Rural Development]\n* [http://www.metal.ntua.gr '''School of Mining and Metallurgical Engineering''']\n** Department of Geological Sciences\n** Department of Mining Engineering\n** Department of Metallurgy and Materials Technology\n* [http://www.naval.ntua.gr '''School of Naval Architecture and Marine Engineering''']\n** Department of Ship Design & Maritime Transport\n** Department of Ship Hydrodynamics\n** Department of Marine Engineering\n** Department of Marine Structures\n{{hidden end}}\n\n===Studies===\n\n====Undergraduate studies====\nThe academic calendar of NTUA comprises 10 independent, integral academic semesters. Each semester lasts 18 weeks: 13 weeks of classes, a two-week break (Christmas and Easter holidays for the fall and spring semester respectively), and three weeks of semester exams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/old/en_academics/undergr.htm|title=NTUA Undergraduate Studies|accessdate=2013-08-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807201303/http://www.ntua.gr/old/en_academics/undergr.htm|archivedate=2013-08-07}}</ref> The 10th semester is devoted to the preparation of the diploma thesis. The diploma thesis has to be related to one of the courses of the faculty. The student has at his or her disposal at least a full academic semester to prepare the thesis. Upon completion of the thesis, the student must take part in an oral examination that can take place either in June, October or February, after the final examinations, provided that the student has passed all courses prescribed by the curriculum.\n\nAn important part of the studies in NTUA are the summer \"training\" projects which take place in Industrial and Production Units, in the period between the end of the spring semester and the beginning of the fall semester. They constitute an elective course for the Faculties of Civil Engineering, Survey Engineering (Surveying and Geodesy Camp) and Mining and Metallurgy Engineering (Mining Camp) and are partially subsidized by the European Union.\n\n====Postgraduate studies====\nThere are currently 20<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntua.gr/el/school/postgraduate-studies|script-title=el:\u039c\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03c0\u03c4\u03c5\u03c7\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03b4\u03ad\u03c2|last=George|website=www.ntua.gr|language=el-gr|access-date=2018-07-01}}</ref> departmental or inter-departmental postgraduate courses, coordinated by NTUA Departments, leading to the respective Post Graduate Specialization Diploma, with a minimum duration of 17 months, including one in Business Administration<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://athensmba.ntua.gr/|title=Athens MBA|website=http://athensmba.ntua.gr/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725161742/http://athensmba.ntua.gr/|archive-date=2010-07-25|url-status=dead}}</ref> (in collaboration with the Athens University of Economics and Business). Moreover, NTUA participates in nine post-graduate programs coordinated by other Greek Universities. After the acquisition of the Post Graduate Specialization Diploma, the student can proceed towards submitting a doctoral thesis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/postgraduate_en.html|title=NTUA Postgraduate Studies|accessdate=2013-08-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807141924/http://www.ntua.gr/postgraduate_en.html|archivedate=2013-08-07}}</ref>\n\n===Academic staff===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+NTUA Academic staff per school\n|+\n|-  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"350px\" | School\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\" | [[Lecturers]]\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\" | '''Associate professors'''\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\" | '''Assistant professors'''\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\" | '''[[Professors]]'''\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\" | '''[[Emeritus]]'''\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\" | '''Total'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| School of [[Applied Mathematics]] and [[Physics]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.semfe.ntua.gr/|title=NTUA, School of Applied Mathematics and Physics|accessdate=2013-08-12}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 5 || 35 || 27 || 40 || 13 || 120\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| School of [[Electrical and Computer Engineering]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ece.ntua.gr/en/staff/faculty|title=NTUA, School of Electrical and Computer Engineering, Faculty|accessdate=2017-09-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161215060953/http://www.ece.ntua.gr/en/staff/faculty|archivedate=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 1 || 11 || 12 || 52 || 20 || 96\n|-\n|  style=\"width:350px; text-align:left;\"| School of [[Civil Engineering]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.civil.ntua.gr/staff/|title=NTUA, School of Civil Engineering, Staff|accessdate=2013-08-12}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; text-align:left;\"| 12 || 16 || 17 || 23 || 13 || 81\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| School of [[Mechanical Engineering]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mech.ntua.gr/gr/staff|title=NTUA, School of Mechanical Engineering, Staff|accessdate=2013-08-12|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131027102306/http://www.mech.ntua.gr/gr/staff|archivedate=2013-10-27}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:100px; \"| 5 || 12 || 8 || 20