s=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n! colspan=10 | QS university subject rankings of NTUA<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.topuniversities.com/universities/national-technical-university-athens#sub |title= QS Stars NTUA University Subject Rankings for 2018|accessdate=2018-05-08}}</ref>\n|-\n! Subject !! 2011 !! 2012 !! 2013 !! 2014 !! 2015 !! 2016 !! 2017 !! 2018 !! 2019 !! 2020\n|-\n| Computer Science and Information Systems || 151-200 || 151-200  || 101-150  || 151-200 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150\n|-\n| Engineering - Chemical || 151-200 || 101-150  || 101-150  || 151-200 || 151-200 || 151-200 || 151-200 || 151-200 || 151-200 || 151-200\n|-\n| Engineering - Civil and Structural || 51-100 || 51-100 || 25  || 28 || 29 || 33 || 42 || 42 || 48 || 39\n|-\n| Engineering - Electrical and Electronic || 51-100 || 51-100 || 51-100  || 51-100 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 51-100 || 101-150 || 51-100\n|-\n| Engineering - Mechanical || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150  || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150\n|-\n| Mathematics || - || - || 151-200  || 151-200 || 201-250 || 201-250 || 251-300 || 251-300 || 301-350 || 201-250\n|-\n| Statistics and Operational Research || 101-150 || 151-200 || 51-100  || 101-150 || 101-150 || 151-200 || - || 151-200 || 151-200 || 151-200\n|-\n| Materials Science || - || - || -  || - || - || - || 201-250 || 251-300 || 251-300 || 301-350\n|-\n| Architecture || - || - || -  || - || - || - || 101-150 || 101-150 || 101-150 || 51-100\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n! colspan=9 | NTU Subject Ranking for NTUA<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nturanking.lis.ntu.edu.tw/Default.aspx|title=NTU Ranking|accessdate=2013-11-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130830195354/http://nturanking.lis.ntu.edu.tw/Default.aspx|archive-date=2013-08-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n|-\n! Subject !! 2011 !! 2012 !! 2013 !! 2014 !! 2015 !! 2016 !! 2017 !! 2018 !! 2019\n|-\n| Computer Science || 127 || 152 || 180 || 195 || 201 || 163 || 163 || 211 || 212\n|-\n| Chemical Engineering || 78 || 95 || 88 || 91 || 118 || 114 || 97 || 83 || 90\n|-\n| Civil Engineering || 87 || 64 || 72 || 70 || 53 || 64 || 72 || 82 || 107\n|-\n| Mechanical Engineering || 77 || 79 || 77 || 53 || 65 || 61 || 57 || 58 || 59\n|}\n\n==Campus==\n\n===Patision Complex===\n[[File:NTUA Patision library.jpg|thumb|260px|NTUA School of Architecture Library at the Patision Complex]]\nThe Averof building is one of the most important and elegant buildings of the Athenian Neoclassical period located in the center of [[Athens]] and the most important work of architect [[Lysandros Kaftanzoglou]]. It constitutes also one of the most important creations of European [[Neoclassicism]], directly influenced in its design by the monuments of the Athenian [[Acropolis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europanostra.org/awards/69/|title=Europa Nostra - The conservation project of the Averof Building|accessdate=2013-08-11}}</ref> Its construction began in 1862 and ended in 1878. After its completion, the building was in continuous use for more than 125 years during which it suffered from several additions and alterations. The main building has housed at times the [[National Gallery (Athens)|National Gallery]] and various exhibitions of [[Heinrich Schliemann|Schliemann]]'s archaeological findings and relics of the 1821 [[Greek revolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arch.ntua.gr/page/28|title=NTUA Architecture School - The Averof Building|accessdate=2013-08-11}}</ref>\n\nThe Averof building reached a deteriorating state and was eventually in great need of restoration and modernization in order to continue operating as an educational establishment. The aim of the conservation project, namely for the Averof to be used again as an educational building, was successfully achieved after the building became operative in the beginning of 2010 and won the grand prize of [[Europa Nostra]] in 2012.\n\n\n===Zografou Campus===\n[[File:Attica 06-13 Hills of Hymettus 15 view.jpg|right|thumb|260px|View of the Zografou campus from Kalogeros hill]]\nThe main campus is located in the [[Zografou]] area of [[Athens]], housing all the schools of NTUA except architecture, which remains in its traditional location on the [[Patision Avenue]] for historical reasons. The main campus spreads over an area of about 190 acres,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://map.ntua.gr/google.htm|title=NTUA Digital Map|accessdate=2010-09-21|publisher=NTUA}}</ref> 6&nbsp;km from the center of [[Athens]]. It includes buildings of 65 acres with fully equipped lecture theaters, laboratories, libraries, gyms, a central library, a computer center and a medical center.\n\nThe School of Applied Mathematics and Physical Sciences is housed in the center of the campus. Right next to it is the Mining and Metallurgical Engineering School. The Civil Engineering School and the Rural and Surveying Engineering School are both housed on the south-west near the Zografou Gate. Mechanical Engineering, Chemical Engineering, Naval Engineering, and the new Electrical Engineering School are all housed near the middle of the campus, while the old electrical engineering buildings remain on the north-east.\n\n====Transportation====\nThere are in-campus roads making all buildings accessible by bicycle and car. There are also various internal buses that allow for transportation within the facilities, driving around the perimeter of the campus and through eight different bus stops. The campus is accessible through three main gates: the [[Katechaki Avenue|Katechaki]] and Kokkinopoulou Gates on the north, and the Zografou Gate on the west. There are 2,000 dedicated parking spots scattered throughout the campus, most nearby all major buildings. The campus resides near the [[Katehaki station|metro station of Katechaki]], which makes it accessible within minutes from any area of Athens. Furthermore, six different buses are available for transportation from various city locations to the campus: the 608 from [[Galatsi]], 230 from [[Acropolis]], 242 from the Katechaki Metro station and 140 from [[Glifada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/visit.html|accessdate=2010-09-21|publisher=NTUA|title=Transportation at NTUA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716094615/http://www.ntua.gr/visit.html|archivedate=2011-07-16}}</ref>\n\n====Central Library====\n[[File:Ntua library.jpg|thumb|Central Library of National Technical University of Athens]]\nOn the campus lies the NTUA Central [[Library]], which has operated since 1914, and was the first library in [[Greece]] with a complete index. Today, it remains one of the largest technical libraries in the country, featuring a collection of over 215,000 books and 100,000 scientific issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.ntua.gr/newsite/el/ghistory.htm|title=History of the NTUA Library|accessdate=2010-09-21|publisher=NTUA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721082646/http://www.lib.ntua.gr/newsite/el/ghistory.htm|archivedate=2011-07-21}}</ref> The library is available to the public at all times for studying, and available to students, faculty, and internal and external researchers for borrowing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.ntua.gr/newsite/el/gborFAQ.htm|title=NTUA Library FAQ|accessdate=2010-09-21|publisher=NTUA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100824085333/http://www.lib.ntua.gr/newsite/el/gborFAQ.htm|archivedate=2010-08-24}}</ref>\n\nThe central library building at Zografou campus houses also the historical library of NTUA as a special collection. This scientific-technical library is unique in Greece, and one of the most important in Europe, since it contains approximately 60,000 volumes and periodicals (1,096 titles) issued from the 17th century until 1950.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.ntua.gr/gr/info/closed_collection.html|title=Special collections of NTUA Library|accessdate=2013-08-09|publisher=NTUA}}</ref> The main bulk of NTUA's historical collection consists of old and rare books, pamphlets, maps, engravings and encyclopedias.\n\n===Other facilities===\n\n====Lavrion Technological and Cultural Park (LTCP)====\nLavrion Technological and Cultural Park (LTCP),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ltp.ntua.gr/home_en|title=NTUA Lavrion Technological and Cultural Park (LTCP)|accessdate=2013-08-10|publisher=NTUA}}</ref> is a body of scientific research, education, business and culture. Founded in place of the old French Mining Company of Lavrion (Compagnie Francaise des Mines du [[Laurium]]) in 1992, as a result of the initiative undertaken from the National Technical University of Athens.\n\nLTCP aims at linking scientific and technological research conducted in Athens with the needs and interests of the business world, and to the realization of cultural events related to the promotion of the history and culture of the wider area of Lavreotiki, and the emergence of the history of activities in the past had developed in the maintenance of premises. The LTCP area is a unique monument of industrial architecture and archeology and placed him in a series of housing facilities for business and research excellence.\n\nThe services provided by LTCP as well as its renovated facilities, continue to support research, education and technology. Today, LTCP is essentially the only technology park in Attica, which specializes in areas - keys of modern applied technology, such as information technology, electronics technology, telecommunications, robotics, technology laser, environmental technology, energy, shipbuilding, marine technology, etc.\n\n====Metsovion Interdisciplinary Research Center (MIRC)====\n[[File:MIRC NTUA.jpg|thumb|MIRC facilities at [[Metsovo]]]]\nThe Metsovion Interdisciplinary Research Center (MIRC) of the National Technical University of Athens for the Protection and Development of Mountainous Environment and Local European Cultures was founded in 1993 by decision of the National Technical University of Athens Senate, following the proposal of the then [[Rector (academia)|Rector]] Professor [[Nikos Markatos]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/MIRC/mekde/mekde-gb.html|title=NTUA Metsovion Interdisciplinary Research Center (MIRC)|accessdate=2013-08-10|publisher=NTUA}}</ref>\n\nThe principal aim of MIRC is to contribute to the protection and development of mountainous environment and local European cultures and the provision of [[continuing education]]. As well as, the conduct of [[research]], studies, [[seminars]] and [[Academic conference|conferences]], relevant to the broader object of MIRC, the creation of a European network with related organizations under the aegis of the center or the participation in already existing networks. The above will be utilized by universities, cultural, research and productive organizations with the aim of assisting [[Metsovon]] in becoming a European center of decentralized interdisciplinary, educational, research, technological and cultural activities of NTUA.\n\n==Culture==\n{{listen\n|filename=NTUA_Choir_-_Lemonaki.ogg\n|title=NTUA Choir&nbsp;\u2013 Lemonaki\n|description=The NTUA choir performing the folk greek song \"Lemonaki\" in a mixed choir rearrangement in 2010\n|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n===Music Department===\nThe NTUA Music Department was established in 1960 by Chancellor Alexander Pappas. The first president of the music department was composer Vassilis Makridis. It features a [[mixed choir]], a [[string orchestra]], and free lessons for various instruments, among others [[piano]], [[guitar]], [[bouzouki]], and [[cello]]. The music department groups regularly perform publicly within the facilities of the university, but also elsewhere. The department president today is [[Conducting|conductor]] and [[composer]] Michalis Economou.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/old/gr_culture/music/music.htm|title=NTUA Music department|publisher=NTUA|accessdate=2010-09-21|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821085746/http://www.ntua.gr/old/gr_culture/music/music.htm|archivedate=2010-08-21}}</ref>\n\n===Dancing Department===\nThe Dancing Department was established in 1990. It is formed by students, and it features various groups, including a Greek traditional and Cretan [[folk dances]] group, a European and [[Latin]] Ballroom dances group, a Salsa and a [[tango]] group. The groups meets weekly, and perform regularly inside and outside the facilities of the university. Attendance and dancing lessons are free for undergraduate and graduate students, alumni, faculty and even people not related to the University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dance.ntua.gr/files/aitisi_eggrafis_17.pdf|title=Dance Club NTUA|last=|first=|date=|website=dance.ntua.gr|access-date=}}</ref> The dancing department is housed near the center of the main campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dance.ntua.gr/|accessdate=2010-09-21|title=Dancing department of NTUA|publisher=NTUA Dancing department}}</ref>\n\n===Theatrical Group===\nThe Theatrical Group was established in 1991. It is a self-managed group, which teaches the art of performance and often performs in public. Participation in the group is free for students. The theatrical group is housed near the center of the main campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/theatre/cv.shtml|title=Theatrical Group History|accessdate=2010-09-21|publisher=NTUA Theatrical Group}}</ref> The theatrical group has also organized a separate percussion lessons group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/theatre/percussion.shtml|title=Percussion Seminar|accessdate=2010-09-21|publisher=NTUA Theatrical Group}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nThe main sports facilities of NTUA are housed in the Sports Center located to the south of the campus, taking up about 3,500 square meters. The campus sport facilities feature [[tennis]] and [[soccer]] courts, a field and track, a [[sauna]], [[ping pong]] tables, and more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://map.ntua.gr/google.htm|accessdate=2010-09-21|title=NTUA Map|publisher=NTUA}}</ref> More than 40 sport teams exist, and the sports practiced include [[aerobic exercise|aerobics]], [[yoga]], [[Pilates]], [[basketball]], [[volleyball]], [[soccer]], [[handball]], [[ping pong]], [[tennis]], [[martial arts]] inside the campus facilities and [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[polo]], [[rowing (sport)|rowing]], [[yachting]], [[rappelling]], [[rafting]], [[Squash (sport)|squash]], [[wind surfing]], and [[equestrianism]] outside.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/announcements/dty/uploads/2009-11-02_348730_invitation.pdf|accessdate=2010-09-21|title=NTUA Sport Center Opening Ceremony|publisher=NTUA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821192746/http://www.ntua.gr/announcements/dty/uploads/2009-11-02_348730_invitation.pdf|archivedate=2010-08-21}}</ref>\n\nEach year several inter-departmental championships are organized among the teams of the university faculties. NTUA student's teams have been distinguished and received many awards in Panhellenic University Games, as well as in university games abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntua.gr/old/en_academics/stud_services.htm#three|accessdate=2010-09-21|title=NTUA Sporting Activities|publisher=NTUA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100731073144/http://www.ntua.gr/old/en_academics/stud_services.htm#three|archivedate=2010-07-31}}</ref>\n\n===Open source===\nThere is an open source students group whose purpose is to promote the use of [[open source software]] throughout the university and beyond.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://foss.ntua.gr/wiki/index.php/%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%B9%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%84%CE%B7%CF%84%CE%B1_%CE%95%CE%BB%CE%B5%CF%8D%CE%B8%CE%B5%CF%81%CE%BF%CF%85_%CE%9B%CE%BF%CE%B3%CE%B9%CF%83%CE%BC%CE%B9%CE%BA%CE%BF%CF%8D_%CE%95%CE%9C%CE%A0|accessdate=2010-09-22|title=Open Source Software Community of NTUA|publisher=Open Source Software Community of NTUA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125070903/http://foss.ntua.gr/wiki/index.php/%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%B9%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%84%CE%B7%CF%84%CE%B1_%CE%95%CE%BB%CE%B5%CF%8D%CE%B8%CE%B5%CF%81%CE%BF%CF%85_%CE%9B%CE%BF%CE%B3%CE%B9%CF%83%CE%BC%CE%B9%CE%BA%CE%BF%CF%8D_%CE%95%CE%9C%CE%A0|archive-date=2010-11-25|url-status=dead}}</ref> Furthermore, NTUA officially supports open source software by using it in its laboratories and other facilities, but also hosting mirrors for all major open source projects <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noc.ntua.gr/index.php?module=ContentExpress&func=display&ceid=35|accessdate=2010-09-22|title=FTP mirrors|publisher=NTUA NOC}}</ref> with a collection of over 2.5 [[terabyte]]s of free and open source software.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftp.ntua.gr/|accessdate=2010-09-22|title=FTP.NTUA.GR|publisher=NTUA}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign languages===\n[[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]] and [[Italian language|Italian]] are the four languages taught in NTUA. All non-exchange students have to choose one from those as a mandatory foreign language course. For foreign students the NTUA Linguistic Service offers the option of attending Greek courses during the entire [[academic year]], free of charge. These courses are intended to provide students with the basic linguistic tools, so that they can understand and communicate efficiently with people in Greece.\n\n==Participation in international organizations==\n* [http://www.cesaer.org CESAER \u2013 Conference of European Schools for advanced Engineering, Education and Research]\n* [http://www.top.upv.es/eegecs/main.asp [[EEGECS]] - Network on European Education in Geodetic Engineering, Cartography and Surveying]\n* [http://www.sefi.be SEFI \u2013 Societe Europeene pour la Formation des Ingenieurs (European Society for Engineering Education)]\n* [https://www.time-association.org TIME \u2013 Top Industrial Managers Europe]\n\n===Student unions===\n* [http://www.fsae.ntua.gr/  NTUA Students' Formula Team]\n* [http://www.mindspace.gr/ Mindspace], an association to promote innovation and entrepreneurship among students\n* Society of Naval Architects and Marine Engineers, NTUA\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130711041522/http://www.ntua.gr/best/athens/#!/Gallery  Athens Local BEST Group]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130902130921/http://eestec.ntua.gr/eestec/en/ Electrical Engineering STudent's European Association Local Committee of Athens (EESTEC)]\n* [http://euroavia.ntua.gr/wordpress/?lang=en Euroavia Athens, NTUA]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130807143141/http://www.ntua.gr/iaeste/ International Association for the Exchange of Students for Technical Experience (IAESTE)]\n*American Institute of Chemical Engineers Student Chapter (AIChE)\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Alexis Tsipras]] - former [[Prime Minister of Greece]]\n* [[Nicholas Ambraseys]] - professor of engineering seismology at [[Imperial College London]]\n* [[Dimitris Anastassiou]] - developer of [[MPEG-2]] algorithm for transmitting high quality audio and video over limited bandwidth and [[Columbia University]] professor of electrical engineering\n* [[John Argyris]] - one of the founders of the [[finite element method]], professor at [[Imperial College London]] and [[University of Stuttgart]]\n* [[Dimitri Bertsekas]] - professor of engineering at [[MIT]]\n* [[Costas Azariadis]] - professor at the Department of Economics, UCLA and Edward Mallinckrodt Distinguished University Professor in Arts & Sciences, Washington University in St. Louis\n* [[Georges Candilis]] - architect and urbanist, one of the founders of [[Team 10]]\n* [[Giorgio de Chirico]] - painter\n* [[Constantine Dafermos]] - Greek applied mathematician, professor at [[Brown University]] and recipient of [[Norbert Wiener Prize in Applied Mathematics]]\n* [[Constantinos Daskalakis]] - computer scientist, professor at [[MIT]]\n* [[Athos Dimoulas]] - poet\n* [[Georgios Gennimatas]] - former MP, minister and founding member of  [[Panhellenic Socialist Movement]]\n* [[John Iliopoulos]] - recipient of the [[Dirac Medal]]\n* [[Paris Kanellakis]] - computer scientist, professor at [[Brown University]]\n* [[Linda P. B. Katehi]] - Chancellor of [[UC Davis]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wascsenior.org/commission/commissioner/linda-katehi|title=Linda Katehi &#124; Senior College and University Commission|accessdate=2014-11-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406013715/http://www.wascsenior.org/commission/commissioner/linda-katehi|archivedate=2015-04-06}}</ref>\n* [[Nikos Markatos]] - former Rector of the NTUA\n* [[Constantine Papadakis]] - former president of [[Drexel University]]\n* [[Christos Papadimitriou]] - computer scientist, laureate of the 2002 [[Knuth Prize]] for longstanding and seminal contributions to the foundations of computer science\n* [[Yannis Papathanasiou]] - politician, former [[Minister for Economy and Finance of Greece]]\n* [[Nicholas A. Peppas]] - professor in engineering, [[University of Texas at Austin]]\n* [[Dimitris Pikionis]] - architect\n* [[George Prokopiou]] - billionaire shipowner<ref name=BloombergProfile>{{cite web|title=George Prokopiou|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profiles/people/18345260-george-prokopiou|website=Bloomberg|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Charalambos Bouras]] - historian, professor of History of Architecture and restoration architect\n* [[Athanasios Roussopoulos]] - professor in applied statics and iron constructions at the National Technical University of Athens, where his work was mostly concerned with the development of the theory of aseismic structures, politician, member of the [[Greek Parliament]] and [[Minister of Public Works]] in 1966, he was also president of the [[Technical Chamber of Greece]]\n* [[Joseph Sifakis]] - computer scientist, laureate of the 2007 [[Turing Award]] for his work on [[model checking]].\n* [[Michael Triantafyllou]] - professor of mechanical and ocean engineering at [[MIT]]\n* [[Ioannis Vardoulakis]] - professor of civil engineering at [[University of Minnesota]] and at NTUA, a pioneer of theoretical and experimental geomechanics\n* [[Iannis Xenakis]] - one of the most important post-war avant-garde composers, pioneer of the use of mathematical models in music and architect\n* [[Mihalis Yannakakis]] - computer scientist, laureate of the 2005 [[Knuth Prize]] for numerous ground-breaking contributions to theoretical computer science\n* [[Mihail Zervos]] - professor of financial mathematics at [[London School of Economics]]\n* Theodosios Tasios - professor of NTUA, author, civil engineer\n*[[Emmanouil Korres]] - professor, writer, restoration architect\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Constantine Papadakis.jpg|President of Drexel University [[Constantine Papadakis]], Civil '69\nFile:Christos Papadimitriou mg 7721-b.cr2.jpg|''Computational Complexity'' author [[Christos Papadimitriou]], ECE '72\nFile:Nicholas A Peppas 1-12-08.jpg|[[Nicholas A. Peppas]], Chemical '71\nFile:Mihalis Yannakakis 2006.jpg|Knuth Prize 2005 winner [[Mihalis Yannakakis]], ECE '75\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Athens Polytechnic uprising]]\n* [[Polytechnic (Greece)]]\n* [[List of universities in Greece]]\n* [[Top Industrial Managers for Europe]]\n* [[Open access in Greece]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|National Technical University of Athens}}\n* [http://www.adip.gr/ Hellenic Quality Assurance and Accreditation Agency (HQAA)] {{in lang|el|en}}\n** [http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_NavalArchMarineEng_%202012.pdf School of Naval Architecture and Marine Engineering, HQAA Final Report, 2012] \n** [http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_MechEng_2012.pdf School of Mechanical Engineering, HQAA Final Report, 2012] \n** [http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_CivilEng_2013.pdf School of Civil Engineering, HQAA Final Report, 2013] \n** [http://www.adip.gr/external/NTUA_ElecCompEng_2013.pdf School of Electrical and Computer Engine